  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and developed over several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged in response to organized crime activities in the early 20th century\n- Initial focus was on combating criminal proceeds from activities like bootlegging and gambling\n\n2. Key Milestones:\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States first established reporting requirements\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established internationally to develop anti-money laundering standards\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention addressed money laundering related to drug trafficking\n- 1990s: Expanded regulations targeting terrorist financing and other criminal proceeds\n- Increasing global cooperation and standardized reporting requirements\n\n4. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- USA PATRIOT Act significantly expanded monitoring and reporting requirements\n- Enhanced international information sharing mechanisms\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n\n5. Modern Era:\n- Continued technological adaptations addressing digital currencies\n- Increased focus on cryptocurrency transactions\n- More sophisticated detection and prevention mechanisms\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
